#Queue using Arrays

Explanation: Definition
1. A queue is a linear data structure that follows FIFO (First In First Out).
The element inserted first is removed first.
2. A queue can be implemented using an array and two variables:
front → points to the first element.
rear → points to the last element.
3. Operations
Enqueue: Adds an element at the rear end.
Dequeue: Removes an element from the front end.
Display: Shows all elements currently in the queue.
4. Advantages and Limitations:
Easy to implement and access elements using array indices.
A fixed size of the array may cause Queue Overflow when full, even if some positions at the front become empty (in a simple queue implementation).

#include <stdio.h>
#define MAX 5

int queue[MAX];
int front = -1, rear = -1;

// Enqueue (Insert)
void enqueue(int value) {
    if (rear == MAX - 1) {
        printf("Queue Overflow\n");
    } else {
        if (front == -1) front = 0;
        rear++;
        queue[rear] = value;
        printf("Inserted: %d\n", value);
    }
}

// Dequeue (Delete)
void dequeue() {
    if (front == -1 || front > rear) {
        printf("Queue Underflow\n");
    } else {
        printf("Deleted: %d\n", queue[front]);
        front++;
    }
}

// Display Queue
void display() {
    if (front == -1 || front > rear) {
        printf("Queue is Empty\n");
    } else {
        printf("Queue elements: ");
        for (int i = front; i <= rear; i++) {
            printf("%d ", queue[i]);
        }
        printf("\n");
    }
}

int main() {
    enqueue(10);
    enqueue(20);
    enqueue(30);

    display();

    dequeue();
    display();

    return 0;
}

